<TITLE> Anti-US activists detained at Kyrgyzstan rally </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BISHKEK, March 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kyrgyzstan's police detained four activists protesting against the presence of US troops on Monday as a US State Department official visited. A group of activists, holding banners reading "Yankee go home!" and chanting anti-US slogans, gathered outside the Foreign Ministry where acting US Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for Central Asia Pamela Spratlen was due to hold talks with Kyrgyz Foreign Minister Ednan Karabayev. The United States set up a military airbase in Kyrgyzstan in 2001 to support operations in Afghanistan, and it is key to Washington's strategic presence in Central Asia. Police dragged the four activists to police buses and drove them away for questioning. A Foreign Ministry official said Spratlen's talks with Karabayev had been postponed to Tuesday but did not link the move to the protest. Kyrgyz people have had mixed feelings about the presence of US troops in their homeland since 2006, when a US airman shot dead a Kyrgyz man at the airbase. The government has rejected calls to evict US troops and defended the airbase's importance. Kyrgyzstan, a former Soviet republic west of China, is also home to a Russian military ba
